<paragraph blockId="9.[192,802,1407,1867]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenço &amp; Leguin, 2012" authorityName="Lourenço &amp; Leguin" authorityYear="2012" box="[240,416,1437,1460]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prudenti" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[240,416,1437,1460]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Buthus prudenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[427,492,1437,1460]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[427,492,1437,1460]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be associated with the “ 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Amoreux" baseAuthorityYear="1789" box="[204,392,1469,1492]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="occitanus">
<emphasis box="[204,392,1469,1492]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Buthus occitanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” complex of species. It can be distinguished from other 
<taxonomicName box="[444,606,1500,1523]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis box="[444,518,1500,1523]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Buthus</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
and in particular from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lourenco" authorityYear="2005" box="[253,458,1531,1554]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elhennawyi">
<emphasis box="[253,458,1531,1554]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Buthus elhennawyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the most geographically close species, by the following characters: (i) Much bigger total size and different morphometric values; see 
<tableCitation box="[721,801,1594,1617]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="4.[192,257,1038,1061]" captionText="Table 1: Morphometric values (in mm) of the male holotype and female paratype of Buthus prudenti sp. * including telson." pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Table 1</tableCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation author="LOURENCO" box="[240,434,1625,1648]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" pagination="245 - 251" refId="ref3077" refString="LOURENCO, W. R. 2005 c. A new species of the genus Buthus Leach, 1815 (Scorpiones, Buthidae) from Senegal and Niger in Western Africa. Entomologische Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum Hamburg, 14 (172): 245 - 251." type="journal article" year="2005">Lourenço (2005c)</bibRefCitation>
; (ii) male pectines in 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenço &amp; Leguin, 2012" authorityName="Lourenço &amp; Leguin" authorityYear="2012" box="[679,801,1625,1648]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prudenti" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[679,801,1625,1648]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. prudenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,261,1656,1679]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[192,255,1656,1679]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
,
</emphasis>
do not overlap in their proximal region, whereas they overlap strongly in males of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lourenco" authorityYear="2005" box="[590,748,1688,1711]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elhennawyi">
<emphasis box="[590,748,1688,1711]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. elhennawyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; the number of pectinal teeth in 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenço &amp; Leguin, 2012" authorityName="Lourenço &amp; Leguin" authorityYear="2012" box="[515,640,1719,1742]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prudenti" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[515,640,1719,1742]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. prudenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[653,716,1719,1742]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is also lower than in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Lourenco" authorityYear="2005" box="[340,491,1750,1773]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elhennawyi">
<emphasis box="[340,491,1750,1773]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. elhennawyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
; (iii) furrows in carapace are more strongly marked in the new species; (iv) male telson of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenço &amp; Leguin, 2012" authorityName="Lourenço &amp; Leguin" authorityYear="2012" box="[300,426,1813,1836]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prudenti" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[300,426,1813,1836]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. prudenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[436,501,1813,1836]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[436,501,1813,1836]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, is almost smooth without any subaculear tooth.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="9.[830,1197,201,229]" box="[830,1197,201,229]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[830,1197,201,229]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Habitat of the New Species</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[830,1441,266,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
The area in which 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenço &amp; Leguin, 2012" authorityName="Lourenço &amp; Leguin" authorityYear="2012" box="[1116,1297,266,289]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prudenti" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1116,1297,266,289]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Buthus prudenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1312,1382,266,289]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1312,1382,266,289]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
was collected is the transitional zone between the Sahel and savannah formations (
<figureCitation box="[1069,1190,328,351]" captionStart-0="Figure 15" captionStart-1="Figures 16–17" captionStartId-0="7.[192,268,1476,1499]" captionStartId-1="8.[192,278,1866,1889]" captionTargetBox-0="[206,1428,201,1438]" captionTargetBox-1="[191,1441,167,1833]" captionTargetId-0="figure-49@7.[192,1438,192,1452]" captionTargetId-1="figure-57@8.[192,1441,168,1832]" captionTargetPageId-0="7" captionTargetPageId-1="8" captionText-0="Figure 15: Map of Western Central Africa, showing the type locality of the new species (black star), and the known distributions of Buthus elizabethae (black circle) and Buthus elhennawyi (black square)." captionText-1="Figures 16–17: Aerial view of the Sanguéré-Djoi region, showing the typical Savannah/Sahel vegetation. In Figure 17 (bottom) one can also observe some agricultural fields (photos by François-Régis Delobal)." pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 15–17</figureCitation>
). Most of these natural formations have been replaced in recent years by agriculture activities. The new species was collected in cotton fields, with the help of Barber traps used to test the efficacy of seed treatment. In present days, most of the area of the Senguéré-Djoi is used for agriculture, but some parcels can also be replaced by others composed of bushes (
<figureCitation box="[918,1048,542,565]" captionStart="Figures 16–17" captionStartId="8.[192,278,1866,1889]" captionTargetBox="[191,1441,167,1833]" captionTargetId="figure-57@8.[192,1441,168,1832]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="Figures 16–17: Aerial view of the Sanguéré-Djoi region, showing the typical Savannah/Sahel vegetation. In Figure 17 (bottom) one can also observe some agricultural fields (photos by François-Régis Delobal)." pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Figs. 16–17</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[830,1441,266,933]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
Two other scorpion species have also been collected in the northern 
<collectingCountry box="[997,1111,604,627]" name="Cameroon" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Cameroon</collectingCountry>
, but in older times when large parcels of the natural environment were yet present: 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenco, Qi et Cloudsley-Thompson, 2006" authorityName="Lourenco, Qi et Cloudsley-Thompson" authorityYear="2006" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Leiurus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="savanicola">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Leiurus savanicola</emphasis>
Lourenço, Qi et Cloudsley-Thompson, 2006
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenco, 2009" authorityName="Lourenco" authorityYear="2009" box="[938,1321,696,719]" class="Arachnida" family="Scorpionidae" genus="Scorpio" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="savanicola">
<emphasis box="[938,1143,696,719]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Scorpio savanicola</emphasis>
Lourenço, 2009
</taxonomicName>
(Lourenço et al., 2006; Lourenço, 2009). It is quite possible, however, that with increasing anthropic action on the environment, most scorpion species will know an important regression of their populations. Only more opportunistic species, what seems to be the case of 
<taxonomicName authority="Lourenço &amp; Leguin, 2012" authorityName="Lourenço &amp; Leguin" authorityYear="2012" box="[1265,1441,849,872]" class="Arachnida" family="Buthidae" genus="Buthus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Scorpiones" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="prudenti" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis box="[1265,1441,849,872]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Buthus prudenti</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[830,895,880,903]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[830,895,880,903]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, will see their populations expand and colonize most of the area (Lourenço, 1991).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
